Put a #large saucepan{} of water with a pinch of @salt{pinch} on to boil for the
pasta. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the
@green chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed and finely chop. Finely chop the
@chives{1/2}. Roughly chop the @serrano ham{2}. 

> TIP: If you've got a pair of sharp kitchen scissors they'll make short work of
> the chives and ham!

Add the @linguine{200%g} and @vegetable stock powder{1/2}(vegetable stock powder) to
the pan of boiling water. Cook until al dente, around ~{6%minutes}. 

> TIP: 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of
> firmness left in the middle.

When the pasta is cooked, drain it in a #colander{}, reserving the pasta stock in
a #measuring jug{}. Drizzle the pasta with a little @olive oil{} to stop it
sticking together.

While the pasta is cooking, heat a splash of @oil{splash} in a #frying pan{} on
medium-high heat. Add the chilli, ham and @king prawns{150%g} and cook for
~{3-4%minutes}. When the prawns have just turned pink, add the garlic. Cook for
~{1%minute} more. Season with a good pinch of salt and @black pepper{}.

Pour @reserved pasta water{50%ml} into the #frying pan{}. Turn the heat to low
and add the @creme fraiche{150%g} and three-quarters of the chives. Simmer for a
few minutes until it goes nice and velvety. If it seems a bit thick, add a little
more pasta stock.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque all the
> way through.

Add the pasta to the sauce. Halve the @lemon{1/2}(halved) and add a good squeeze
of lemon juice. Taste and add a little more salt and pepper if necessary. Stir
gently to combine everything.

Serve in #bowls{} with a sprinkle of the remaining chives on top. Tuck in!